# Testing

## Structure

```
tests/
├── Unit/              # Services, models, commands, scopes
└── Feature/Api/       # One test class per endpoint action
    ├── Auth/, Events/, Checkout/, Volunteering/, Grants/, Admin/, Me/
```

## API Tests

Extend `ApiRouteTestCase` (not `TestCase` directly):

```php
class EventIndexTest extends ApiRouteTestCase
{
    public bool $seed = true;
    public string $routeName = 'api.events.index';

    #[Test]
    public function event_index_call_as_admin_returns_all_events(): void
    {
        $user = User::role(RolesEnum::Admin)->firstOrFail();
        $response = $this->actingAs($user)->get($this->endpoint);
        $response->assertStatus(200);
    }
}
```

- `ApiRouteTestCase` provides `LazilyRefreshDatabase`, `$routeName`/`$routeParams` → `$endpoint`, and JWT `actingAs()`
- Use PHPUnit `#[Test]` attributes (not `test_` prefix methods)
- Name tests descriptively: `{resource}_{action}_{scenario}`
- Seed permissions/roles via `$seed = true` + `givePermissionTo()` or `RolesEnum`
- Use named routes (`api.events.index`) — never hardcode URLs

## Configuration

- `DB_CONNECTION=testing` uses a dedicated `testing` MySQL database
- API test suite is commented out in `phpunit.xml` — enable the `Api` testsuite to run them in CI
- JWT keys required for API tests (see `.github/workflows/testing.yml` for CI setup)

## Factories

Use domain-namespaced factories with states: `EventFactory::active()`, `TicketTypeFactory::notTransferable()`.
